s' access to credit is intimately bound up with identity, status-making, and aspirations of upward mobility. She draws out the deeply precarious nature of both the aspirations and the economic relations of debt which sustain her subjects, revealing the shadowy side of indebtedness and its potential to produce new forms of oppression and disenfranchisement in place of older ones. Money from Nothing uniquely captures the lived experience of indebtedness for those many millions who attempt to improve their positions (or merely sustain existing livelihoods) in emerging economies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBlackszSouth AfricaxEconomic conditions. 0aBlackszSouth AfricaxSocial conditions. 0aConsumer creditzSouth Africa. 0aConsumption (Economics)zSouth Africa. 0aDebtzSouth Africa. 0aSocial mobilityzSouth Africa. 0aSocial statuszSouth Africa. 4aImpalahoek (Mpumalanga). 4aSouth Africa. 4aSoweto (Gauteng). 4aaspiration. 4adual economy. 4aindebtedness. 4amiddle class. 4aproperty. 4aredistribution. 4ashaping subjectivities. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479315540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804793155423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804793155.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles